In the transaction, Peoples purchased loans, including accrued interest, with a fair value of $21,365, and premises and equipment with a fair value of $1,368, in addition to assuming deposits, including accrued interest, with a fair value of $40,802. No new capital was raised by Peoples for the purchase, which was funded by existing capital levels. In the transaction, Peoples received a net cash payment from Baraboo totaling $17,460, net of a purchase premium paid by Peoples of $654. Under the purchase accounting applied to the transaction, Peoples recognized a core deposit intangible of $231, to be amortized over a 5 year period using the double declining balance method, and recognized $113 of purchase goodwill. During the six months ended June 30, 2014, approximately $371 of merger and conversion non-recurring expenses were recorded in connection with the branch purchase.

Under the merger, CBD survived with new shareholders and new management. Buckeye Nation Interim, Inc., was dissolved effective the date of the merger. The merger led to the GAAP requirement of using Purchase Accounting for adjustments to the balance sheet. Under Purchase Accounting Loan and Lease Losses are effectively eliminated and replaced with Purchase Accounting Credit Component, which acts similar to ALLL. The amount of the Credit Component was $159,000 at 3/31/14, and $144,000 as of 6/30/14.
